<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-523-808  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 523 808.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 11 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber cable for medicine.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Atlantic Corp. (services)Corabi Telemetrics International Inc. (innovations).andO;Ticker:    BEL.andO;Topic:     Fiber opticsMedical DiagnosisHigh-Definition TelevisionApplications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FIBER CABLE FOR MEDICINE WILMINGTON, DELAWARE, U.S.A., 1989 JUL 3 (NB) --Bell Atlantic is aggressively laying optical fiber so pathologists can studytissue samples remotely using high definition TV pictures.andP;  CorabiTelemetrics of Alexandria, Virginia, developed the system, which is billed asa revolutionary advance in diagnostic technology.andP;  Ikegami, a Japanesecompany, is providing high definition TV technology so the system can producea sharp enough image for remote diagnoses.andP;  Corabi hopes to make the nation'scapital a test market for its product, and plans to announce the names ofarea hospitals which will use it in the next few weeks.andP;  Two hospitals inAtlanta are already using it, but the need for high-capacity optical fiber,and Corabi's location in Northern Virginia, moved it to seek a phone companypartner for the wider market test.andP;  &quot;With our aggressive fiber policy, we caninstall almost anywhere in the metro area,&quot; said Larry Litteral, a technologyplanner at Bell Atlantic.andP;  The $100,000 telepathology system is the firstproduct for Corabi, which was founded five years ago by Chicago pathologistRonald Weinstein.andP;  Corabi provides a robotized microscope on which a labsample can be placed at the hospital.andP;  The doctor at the other end of thelink is provided with a high-resolution monitor.andP;  Using a joystick, thepathologist then moves the microscope lens to examine the image on themonitor.andP;  The link to Bell Atlantic is important to Corabi for anotherreason.andP;  Using satellites to transmit HDTV images is far more costly, Corabiadmits.andP;  That's some admission, considering it's part-owned by CommunicationsSatellite Corp., or Comsat.andP;  (Dana Blankenhorn/19890707/Press Contact: BellAtlantic, Larry Litteral, 703-974-5415)</TEXT></DOC>